<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="211" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="10" pageNumber="211">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,295,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="211">Remarks.</emphasis>
Although the sample size is small, this appears to be one of the few Auchenorrhyncha in which males are distinctly larger than macropterous females. The only previous reported case in Cercopoidea (
<bibRefCitation author="Paladini" pageId="10" pageNumber="211" refString="Paladini, A. (2011) A new species of Ferorhinella with an unusual pattern of sexual size dimorphism (Hemiptera, Cercopidae, Tomaspidinae). Zootaxa, 2728, 57 - 60." type="journal article" year="2011">Paladini 2011</bibRefCitation>
) is based on a submacropterous female in which the tegmina are abbreviated and the hindwings absent whereas the male is macropterous.
</paragraph>
